In Japan, when abnormalities were observed, {{ill|Tenmon Hakase|ja|天文博士|1=Tenmon Hakase|12=draft}} (including assistant Tenmon Hakase) or individuals granted a Tenmon Mitsusō {{ill|Senji|ja|宣旨|12=draft}} were required to interpret the phenomena based on past cases and submit a sealed report, through the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|12=draft}}, to the {{ill|Emperor of Japan|ja|天皇|12=draft}}. The {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老律令|12=draft}}’s {{ill|Zatsuryō|ja|雑令|12=draft}} specifies: "If there are minor auspicious or inauspicious events, report them to the Onmyōryō. Afterward, seal them seasonally and send them to the Ministry of the Interior to be archived in the national records." This bypassing of the {{ill|Daijōkan|ja|太政官|12=draft}}, the highest organ of governance, reflected the emperor's exclusive responsibility for astronomical matters. In later periods, the content of these reports was reviewed and resealed by the Daijōkan or {{ill|Sesshō and Kampaku|ja|摂政・関白|12=draft}} before being resubmitted to the Onmyōryō (as described in works such as {{ill|Saigūki|ja|西宮記|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shingi-shiki|ja|新儀式|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kinjishō|ja|禁秘抄|12=draft}}). Portions of the reports pertaining to predictions were deemed state secrets and excluded from official records managed by {{ill|Naiki|ja|内記|12=draft}}.

The documents used for such divinations included the {{ill|Tenmon Yōroku|ja|天文要録|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shinsen Onmyō-sho|ja|新撰陰陽書|12=draft}}, {{ill|Teiran|ja|帝覧|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tenmonroku|ja|天文録|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tenchi Zuisenshō|ja|天地瑞祥志|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shishō Sukuyō-kyō|ja|指掌宿曜経|12=draft}}, {{ill|Senji Ryakketsu|ja|占事略决|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Rekirin|ja|暦林|12=draft}}.

After the establishment of the {{ill|Kurōdodokoro|ja|蔵人所|12=draft}}, Tenmon Hakase bypassed the Onmyōryō and submitted reports directly to the {{ill|Kurōdo|ja|蔵人|12=draft}}, who relayed them to the emperor. In urgent cases, such as late at night or early morning, Tenmon Hakase were allowed to report directly to the emperor. The {{ill|Kinjishō|ja|禁秘抄|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft}} notes that Tenmon Hakase and qualified secret envoys must immediately report any celestial phenomena to the {{ill|Nairan|ja|内覧|12=draft}}, or regent, without concern for their attire.

Over time, during the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft}}, Tenmon Mitsusō privileges became restricted to the {{ill|Abe clan|ja|阿倍氏|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nakahara clan|ja|中原氏|12=draft}}, both of which had deep connections to {{ill|family knowledge|ja|家学|12=draft}} of astrology and astronomy. Notably, during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft}}, even the {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂朝臣氏|12=draft}}, associated with calendar-making, were occasionally granted Tenmon Mitsusō rights.
*
